.TH SIMPLE_SHELL 1 "MAY 2026" "Systems Engineering" "Linux User's Manual"
.SH NAME
hsh \- Custom Unix command-line interpreter (shell)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./hsh
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a minimalist command language interpreter that executes commands read from standard input streams or specialized text pipes. It serves as a practical implementation of standard Unix shell architectures, providing essential subsystem routing and environment manipulation.

The software operates via two distinct execution pathways:
.TP
.B Interactive Mode
The application issues a continuous user prompt (\fB#cisfun$\fR) onto standard output, waiting to capture, parse, and execute entered command strings interactively.
.TP
.B Non-Interactive Mode
When commands are piped or redirected into the shell (e.g., via echo or files), \fBhsh\fR processes the input sequentially until reaching an End-Of-File (EOF) token, then exits cleanly.
.SH CORE FEATURES
.SS Built-in Commands
The interpreter natively implements internal routing operations without spawning child forks:
.TP
.B exit
Smoothly terminates the current shell runtime environment, passing the status of the last executed process back to the parent operating system.
.TP
.B env
Retrieves and prints all inherited system environment variables and text structures seamlessly to standard output.
.SS Path Resolution
If an entered command does not contain a forward slash (/), the shell dynamically searches through directories listed in the \fBPATH\fR environment variable to locate and execute the corresponding binary.
.SS Signal Management
Traps terminal interruptions dynamically. Pressing \fBCtrl+C\fR (\fBSIGINT\fR) resets the current buffer, prints a fresh newline, and re-displays the prompt without crashing the shell environment.
.SS Conditional Chaining
Accommodates basic inline logical execution sequences:
.TP
.B &&
Executes the subsequent statement if and only if the prior targeted program exits with an absolute success status code (0).
.TP
.B ||
Executes the following command block if and only if the previous process fails and returns a non-zero exit status.
.SH DIAGNOSTICS
Upon encountering an unregistered command or invalid path, \fBhsh\fR prints a standard error format to stderr:
.I "./hsh: 1: command_name: not found"
and returns an exit status code of 127.
